{"/service/ndnp/mthi/batch_mthi_lynx_ver01/data/sn84036008/00212476584/1907102901/0694.xml":{"full_text":"LOCAL AND PERSONAL\nememem~mema\nMrs. Langley of Forsyth, visited\nfriends in the city Snday.\nC. J. Baldwin, a lumberman of\nBridger, was a Billings visitor Sun\nday.\nDr. J. H. Riesland of Helena is in\nthe city, accompanied by Mrs. Reis\nland.\nR. P. Parker, an attorney of Sheri\ndan, Wyo., is in the city on legal busi\nness.\nAttorney R. E. Noyes left yesterday\nmorning for Seattle on a short busi\nness trip.\nA. L. Corey, a rancher of Carbon\ncounty, was in the city Sunday from\nRed Lodge.\nIMajor J. E. Edwards of Forsyth,\nspent yesterday in the city calhing\non old friends.\nC. T. Thomas, a well known wool\ngrower of Lake Basin, is in the city\nattending to business affairs.\nW. W. Clark, a business man and\n\"booster\" of Columbus, spent a part\nof yesterday here on business.\nH. N. Savage, supervising engineer\nof the United States reclamation ser\nvice, was a Billings visitor yesterday.\nO. F., Goddard has returned from\nan eastern trip which included short\nstays in New York city and Washing\nton.\nGeorge Gordon left yesterday morn\ning for his ranch on the ceded strip\nof the reservation, located near San\nders.\nC. D. Howe of the United States\nreclamation service, stationed at\nHuntley, spent Sunday visiting\nfriends in this city.\nW. W. Worthington, manager of the\nMmonttna Coal and Iron company's\nmines near Bear 'Creek, was a Billings\nvisitor over Sunday.\nF. A. Hall, president of the Yellow\nstone Park railway, with headquarters\nat Belfry, spent Sunday here, accom\npanied by Mrs. Hall.\nMr. and Mrs. Sam Connelly, for\nmerly residents of this city but at\npresent located at Pryor agency, are\nvisiting friends here.\nMrs. George Dulin of Red Lodge,\nwho has been visiting her daughter\n'Mrs. Martin for the past week re\nturned to her home yesterday.\nD. MaMahan and daughter, Miss\nNellie of Montreal, Canada, left yester\nday for their homes after visiting their\nson and brother Joseph McMahan of\nNorth Twenty-eighth street.\nWilliam C. 'Smith of Everett, Pa.,\narrived in the city Friday and will\nmake his home here in the future.\nMr. Smith is a railroad man and was\nformerly yardmaster at Dallas, Pa.\nS. IN. Nicholson, U. S. revenue col\nlector for the district of Montana with\nheadquarters at Helena, stopped over\nin the city Sunday en route home\nfrom a trip to the eastern part of the\nstate.\nRev. H. Samuel Fritsch of Somo.\nnauk, Ill., returned to his home yes\nterday morning after a short stay in I\nthe city, during which he occupied the'\npulpit at the Congregational church,\nSunday.\nMiss Hilda West daughter of Mr.\nand 'Mrs. A. H. West, former residents\nof this city but at present residing in\nMissouli, left for her home yesterday\nafter spending severas days in the\ncity visiting friends.\nFrom Sunday's Daily.\nT. J. Walsh, an attorney of Helena,\nis in the city attending court.\nMiss Clara Lamport of Bear Creek,\nis visiting friends in the city.\n0. E. Beaver, a business man of\nCuster, was in the city yesterday.\nW. W. Worthington, a business man\nof Bear Creek, spent yesterday in the\ncity.\nE. L. Erickson returned yesterday\nfrom a weeks sojourn at the Rosebud\nlakes.\nWalter Lamport returned yesterday\nfrom a short business trip to Bear\nCreek.\nHarry F. Scoot, a Junction mer\nchants was a business visitor here yes\nterday.\nRalph E. Reber, a real estate man\nof Joliet, was a Billings visitor yes\nterday.\nW. F. Meyer, a 'Red Lodge attorney,\nspent yesterday in the city on legal\nbusines.\nW. A. Talmage, familiarly called\n\"Sycamore Bill' by his friends is in\nthe city from Red Lodge. Mr Tal\nmage is one of the poineer business\nmen of the coal camnp.\nelp the Horse\nNo article is more useful,\nabout the stable than Mica,\nAxle Grease. Put a little on\nthe spindles before you \"hook\nn \"-it will help the horse, and\nbring the load home quicker.\nMIO0 AILE\nGREASE\nwears well-better than any\nother grease Coats the axle\n-with t lpard smooth surface of\npowderdd mica which reduces\nfriction Ask the dealer for\nMica Axle Grease.\nrruurr bw a\nP. A. Cassidy, a popular hotel clerk\nof Columbus was a Billings visitor\nyesterday.\nBenard Blum, a surveyor of Laurel\narrived in the city last night and will\nspend Sunady here.\nMrs. W. H. Donovan of North\nThirty-first street, returned yesterday\nfrom an eastern trip.\nSam Gebo, a coal operator of From\nberg, stopped over in the city last\nnight en route home from an eastern\ntrip.\n-Mr. and Mrs. C. S. Marvin of Lau\nrel are spending Sunday here. Mr.\nMarvin is cashier of the First National\nbank at Laurel.\nRev. H. Samuel Fritsch of Somo\nnauk, Ill., arrived in the city yester\nday and will occupy the pulpit at the\nCongregational church this morning.\nMiss Maude Anderson, money order\nclerk of the local postoffice, has re\nsigned and will start for Minneapolis\nshortly, where she will accept a posi\ntion with a large printing concern.\nH. Barr, a rancher of Park City,\nwho has achieved some fame in bee\nculture was in the city yesterday.\nT. J. Johns, formerly editor of the\nRed Lodge Republican, is in the city,\naccompanied by Mrs. Johns and little\nson.\nMr. and Mrs. J. C. Hays and two\nsons left yesterday for Lincoln, Neb.,\nwhere they go to attend the wedding\nof Mr. Hays' sister, which will take\nplace the last day of this month. Mr.\nHays is local agent for the Northern\nand Adams Express companies in this\ncity.\nFrom Saturday's Daily.\nC. E. Snyder and wife of Lavina,\nare visiting friends in the city.\nMiss Claire Strong is convalescing\nfrom an attack of typhoid fever.\nT. -S. Davis, a lumberman of Colum\nbus, was a Billings visitor yesterday.\nJohn Schoeder, a wool grower of\nLake Basin, is in the city on business.\nAerlod B. Neate, a rancher of Car\nbon county, is in the city from Brid,\nger.\nW. R. Westbrook, a business man\nof Laurel, was a Billings visitor yes\nterday.\nAttorney Charles Harris left yester\nday morning for Columbus on legal\nbusiness.\nAssistant Postmaster George Book\ner is confined to his home with a se\nvere cold.\nE. J; McLean, city treasurer of Red\nLodge, was calling on old friends in\nthe city yesterday.\nAttorney William Gallagher left yes\nterday for Columbus to take part in a\nlahd contest which is being held there.\nCecil Parhsan left yesterday morn\ning for his ranch near Joliet to super\nintend the harvesting of his beet crop.\nNick Klos returned yesterday from\nMinnesota where he was called re\ncently by an announcement of the\ndeath of ssister.\nH. E. Wolfe, secretary and trea\nsurer of the Farmers Trading com\npany of Bridger, was a business visit\nor to the city yesterday.\nEd. H. Corle, a former resident of\nthis city but at present a rancher of\nCarbon county, is in the city, calling\non old friends, from Joliet.\nMiss Jennie Stoddard of South\nTwenty-eighth, street has returned\nhome after a 10-days' visit with Mr.\nand Mrs. Chris Donehue of Livingston.\nL. J. Daly, a former resident of\nthis city, but more recently of Mis\nsoula, has returned to this city and\nexpects to locate here in the. near fu\nture.\nJ. M. Combs of Geneva, Neb., who\nhas been visiting his brother W. A.\nCombs of North Thirty-first street for\nseveral days, returned to his home\nyesterday.\nHerman Sightzinger left yesterday\nmorning for a trip to Butte, during\nwhich he will combine 'business with\npleasure and take in the sights of the\ngreat copper camp.\nEarl Bell, formerly connected with\nthe Canadian Pacific Railroad com\npiny, in the Northwest, is in the city\nvisiting his brother, C. S. Bell of\nYellowstone avenue.\nG. A. Stockwell left yesterday for\na business trip to the Pacific coast.\nMrs. Stockwell accompanied her hus\nband as far as Helena where she will\nvisit friends for some time.\nFred Hine, county surveyor of Car\nbon county, left yesterday morning\nfor his home at Red Lodge after\nspending Thursday in the city, at\ntendink the trial of the White Horse\nditch cases.\n'Mr. and Mrs. Louis Babcock of\nNorth Twenty-ninth street, returned\nyesterday from a month's trip to the\neastern cities during which they vis\nited for some time in New York and\nPhiladelphia.\nGeorge W. Trask of Utica, is in the\ncity visiting his mother, Mrs. W. P.\nTrask and his sister 'Mrs. J. S.\nSimineo, of North Thirty-fourth street.\nMr. Trask is shipping a number of\ncars of cattle to the eastern market.\nMr. and Mrs. Bernard Keys of Wor\nland, Wyo., arrived in the city yes\nterday and will remain for several\ndays, making their fall purchases. Mr.\nKeys is the Burlington agent at Wor\nland and this is his first visit to Bill\nings. He is favorably impressed with\nthe .city.\nITEMS PICKED\nUP CASUALLY\nTHINGS NOTED AND HEARD\nABOUT THE CITY STREETS.\nHOTELS AS CLUBS\nThe Clerk Explains His View of the\nMatter-A Collision Which Harmed\nNo One-Searching for a Dog\nAmong a Myriad of Dogs.\n\"I venture to say,\" began the hotel\nclerk, \"that more business is done in\nthe loblbies of hotels than in the offices\nof business houses. The hotel, par\nticularly in a moderate sized town, is\nthe gathering place of the business\nmen, a concourse for leisure hours of\nmany of the prominent men of the\ntown.\n\"Here they gather for a chat in the\nevening, and here they frequently, in\nthe course of conversation, formulate\nand perhaps put through deals for\nlarge sums and of much importance.\n\"One thing which makes.the hotel\na concourse and almost a 'bourse'\nfor merchants and other business\nmen, is the fact that commercial trav\nelers have their sample rooms in. the\nhotel and bring the merchant to the\nrooms to look over their samples.\nand when evening comes they often\nbring the merchant over to close a\ndeal and then, with cigars alight, sit\ndown in the lobby. Later more men\ndrop in, until in the middle of the\nevening you will find the hotel office\na gathering of business men, lawyers,\narchitects, physicians, in fact a rep\nresentative crowd of the first men in\nthe city. For this it beats even the\nclubs.\"\nA Collision.\nThere was a funny Incident yester\nday in front of Lanstrum's cigar store.\nA man walking with head erect,\nsearching for a sign in an upper win\ndow, and a woman, looking over her\nshoulder and pushing a baby carriage,\nwere going in opposite directions. The\nman strode ahead with long, swinging\nsteps; the woman, still intent on what\nshe saw over her shoulder, moved at\na rapid pace.\nWell, they met. The baby carriage\ncaught the man just above the knees,\nand he fell over on the baby. The\nshock nearly upset the woman and\nshe fell over on the man. With much\neffort they extricated themselves, and\nthe man, fearing that he had hurt the\nchild, looked down to see.\nBut the baby only said, \"da, da,\"\nand all was peace and love.\nThe Lost Dog.\n\"I lost a dog the other day,\" re\nmarked the man who usually is talk\ning, \"and I went out to find him. He\nwas mostly just dog, but I thought a\ngood deal of the pup and wanted him\nhome. There wasn't anything much\nto distinguish him by, either-he\nlooked like a good many other dogs.\n\"Now, I claim to have pretty good\neyesight, but if there was one dog\nwhich looked like mine yesterday,\nthere were 25, and I came near hav\ning my hands bitten off in trying to\ncatch them. And when I finally got\nmy own dog, as I did, and started\nhome, there were 1,250 doigs trailing\nme. They had been gathering in\ndroves all the while I searched, and\nthey trailed me for at least a mile:\nAnd then I remembered that I had a\npackage of sausage in my overcoat\npocket which I had bought for sup\nper, and the mystery was solved.\n\"But honest, I never knew before\nhow many dogs there are in this city.\nI think there are more dogs than\nthere are children, and this is no race\nsuicide town~ either.\"\nMARRIED IN BILLINGS.\nAlvy C. Borrows and Elsie Bitle Are\nMade One.\nAlvy C. Borrows, who is a minor,\naged 20, was Saturday granted a li\ncense to wed Miss Elsie M. Bitle,\naged 21. Both the contracting par\nties are residents of Billings.\nAs Mr. Borrows is a minor, the\nconsent of his guardian, W. H. Bor\nrows, was necessary and this consent\nis granted nnder oath by the gual\ndian.\nThe young couple were married\nSunday night at the home of W. H.\nBorrows, the groom's brother, by the\nRev. B. Z. McCollough. A wedding\nsupper was served after the cere\nmony.\nWILL OPEN BRANCH\nHOUSE IN THIS CITY\nBOOTH AND COMPANY TO DIS\nTRIBUTE FROM BILLINGS.\nA. Booth company, the largest\nfish and oyster house in the world will\nestablish a branch house in this city\nnext spring according to O. S. An\ndrews, traveling representative of the\ncompany, who was in Billings Satur\nday. The company has branch houses\nin Chicago, Denver, St. Paul, Seattle\nand many other of the larger cities in\nthe United States, and have decided\nthat Billings is the most feasible dis\ntributing point in this section of the\ncountry.\nThrough the'Billings branch the com\npany will distribute their wares to the\nstate of Montana, Northern Wyoming,\nand a portion of the Dakotas and\nIdaho; Being the only distributing\npoint between St. Paul and Seattle,\nthe amount of business done by the\ncompany through their branch house\nin this city will be enormous.\n,During his stay here Mr. Andrews\ncompleted the preliminary arrange\nments for the establishment of the\nhouse and representatives of the\nhouse will return at a later date and\ncomplete all the arrangements before\nspring.\nOLD BANKRUPTECY\nCASE IS SETTLED\nCREDITORS FAIL TO SECURE AS\nSIGNED JUDGMENT.\nThe final report of Alva Mayne,\ntrustee of the estate of Joseph Furley,\nof Livingston who has been adjudged\na bankrupt was filed with Referee\nFrith yesterday. Furley was adjudged\na bankiupt more than a year ago and\nat that time did not have any assets\nbeyond a judgment which he obtained\nin the district court in Park county for\n$1,400.\nLitigation has been in progress over\nthis judgment for some time and the\ntrustee was seeking to to get an as\nsignment of the judgment which Fur\nley had made to a firm of real estate\nmen, set aside. The creditors bore\nthe expenses and costs of the case but\nwere unsuccessful in their efforts to\nget the assignment set aside as it was\nshown that Furley had put the money\nobtained by assigning the judgment\ninto his business.\nMEMBERS INVITED\nTO ATTEND DINNER\nSECRETARY DECKER ASKED TO\nRESPOND TO TOAST.\nFrom Saturday's 'Daily.\nSecretary Jean Decker of the cham\nber of commerce, is in receipt of a\ncommunication Prom the Sheridan,\nViyo., commercial club in which the\nmembers of the local organization\nare invited to attend the annual din\nner of the members of the club, which\nis to be held in the northern Wyo\nming metropolis November 15.\nThe letter urges. an acceptance of\nthe invitation by all of the members\nof the Billings Chamber of Commerce,\nand especially urges. Mr. Decker to be\npresent and respond to the toast,\n\"The Evolution of a Booster.\"\nThe idea of giving an annual din\nner is being talked: of seriously by a\nnumber of members of the local or\nganization, and the plan will in all\nprobability 'be brought up at the next\nmeeting of the chamber of commerce.\nGAME CALLED AT\nTHE END OF NINTH\nDARKNESS PUTS END TO CON\nTEST AT CENTRAL PARK.\nAt the end of the ninth inning the\nbaseball game between the Billings\nAll Stars and a team from Park City,\nplayed Sunday at Central park, was\ncalled on account of darkness with\nthe score 8 to 8.. Owing to numerous\nerrors on the part of players of both\nteams, many unearned runs were\nmade.\nAt times the All Stars would steady\ndown and play good ball for a couple\nof innings, and then would allow Park\nCity to score two or three times. The\nvalley boys followed the same pro\ncedure, seemingly, as the All Stars\nscored in spurts also. Searles, the\nPark City catcher, made a number of\nfine throws to second, and the all\naround good playing of Carr and\nJohnston, on third and at short, were\nfeatures of the game. A number of\nthe All Stars did not show their usual\ngood form, or Park City would not\nhave been permitted to score.\nBrown pitched the first five innings\nfor the Stars and was succeeded by\nCarrier, according to prearrangement.\nAll of the pitchers tossed good ball,\nbut received miserable support at\ntimes.\nLatest styles in Job Printing at the\nGazette Office.\nA complete score of a new opera\nby Verdi, the existence of which has\nhitherto been unknown has been dis\ncovered in Paris in an old chest full\nof manuscripts and other papers which\nformerly belonged to the famous musi\ncian. It was the composition of this\nopera which occupied some of the\nlatter months of Verdi's life.\nCOFFEE\nGood grocers like Schil\nling's Best, for it makes\ngood-will and not trouble\nin case of complaint, the\nmoney is ready.\nYour grocer returns yoaur money if you don't\nlie it: we pay him\nWESLEYAN IS\nTHE OLDEST\nPRESIDENT TELLS OF MONTANA'S\nUNIVERSITY.\nWONDERFUL GROWTH\nDuring Financial Panic of Early Nine\nties Had Hard Struggle for Exist\nense, But Finally Surmounted Diffi\nculties-Among Leading Institutions.\n,President R. P. Smith of the Mon\ntana Wesleyan university spent Sun\nday in the city representing the inter\nests of that institution and visiting\nhis brother, Rev. Edward Smith, pas\ntor of the First Methodist church. Mr.\nSmith claims that the Wesleyan uni\nversity is the oldest college with an\nunbroken history in the state.\n\"The university was founded in\n1889,\" said he in an interview. \"Dur\ning its brief history it has assisted in\nthe education of some 1,300 of the\nboys and girls of Montana. Many\nteachers holding responsible positions\nin different parts of the state re\nceived their normal training in this\ninstitution. Some 30 preachers filling\nresponsible pulpits in ths and' sur\nrounding states received their training\nin part or entirely in this school. Rev.\nC. D. Crouch, holding one'of the most\nconspicuous and responsible pulpits of\nthe state, that in the First church of\nGreat Falls, received all his training\nin the Montana Wesleyan. Likewise\nRev. P. W. Haynes, at Fort Benton,\nPresiding Elders U. F. Hawk of the\nSpokane district and Edward Laird\nMills of the Helena district, this state,\nboth received their early training in\nthe Wesleyan. A number of the\nyounger lawyers, doctors and newspa\nper men of the state laid the founda\ntion for their careers in this school.\n\"The institution at present is doing\nchiefly academic work, including the\nfreshman year of the colIgiate depart\nment. It sustains a normal, commer\ncial, musical and elocutionary depart\nments.\nStruggle for Existence.\n\"During the financial panic and\nhard times of the early nineties the\nschool had a real struggle for exist\nence, and but a few years ago the\nchurch was seriously considering\nabandoning the enterprise. It was only\ntwo years ago the board of trustees\nannounced a forward movement.\nSince that time the school has enjoyed\na remarkable growth. The boys and\ngirls and faculty were then housed in\none dormitory. Kerosene lamps were\nstill in use, and much of the furniture\nwas 15 years old. Stoves, furniture\nand buildings were in the worst sort\nof repair. The preceding year had\nclosed with a student body numbering\nnot over 35. There was a floating\ndebt of $8,625.\n\"In two years the debt has been can\ncelled, new furniture installed\nthroughout, electric lights put in and\nall buildings have been thoroughly\nrenovated, repaired, calsomined and\npainted. Separate dormitories have\nbeen provided for boys and girls, This\nin itself marked' an epoch in the de\nvelopment of the school. Last year\nwe had 154 students, and are now so\ncrowded that we fear to do extensive\nadvertising. The faculty has been al\nmost doubled in numbers and their\nsalaries materially increased and\npromptly paid. Our educational col\nlections from the churches have been\nalmost trebled, amounting last year\nto over $2,800.\n\"A sustaining fund of about $2,000\nper year for a period of five years has\nbeen built up. Confidence in the\nschool throughout the church and\nstate has been restored. A will, giv\ning a two-thirds interest in a proper\nty worth $5,000 or $6,000 has recently\nbeen made in our favor. A new cam\npus consisting of over six solid blocks,\nwithin two blocks of the capitol build\ning, and in one of the most conspicu\nous and beautiful locations In the city\nof Helena, has been purchased and\npaid for in full. This property now is\nprobably worth $10,000, and its acqui\nsition alone more than justifies our\nforward movement.\n\"In view of this recent rapid devel\nopment of the school, the board of\ntrustees only a few months ago\nraised the slogan, 'one hundred thous\nand dollars for a larger Montana Wes\nleyan,' and in the past few weeks $14,\n000 have been offered on the condi\ntion this amount be raised in full.\nHas Considerable Property.\n\"The institution has acquired con\nsiderable property. It owns a good\nranch in Fergus county of 160 acres,\n205 acres of land near the city'of Hel\nena with an unused building on it the\nmaterial of which is worth $7,000\nthis was originally used by the school,\nbut the removal of the street cars ne\ncessitated its temporary abandonment\n-two good buildings in the city of\nHelena and rents two others, a new\ncampus site of about 24 acres near\nthe capitol building, three lots in\nWhitehall, and a small, unproductive\nlegacy of $3,000. The Montana Wes\nleyan university is rapidly taking its\nplace among the leading institutions\nof learning in the northwest.\"\nT\u00fde Very Latest.\nThe very' latest designs in Ladies'\nEngraved Calling Cards and Embossed\nNote Paper and Envelopes at The Ga\nzette office.\nRUB BBER\nRubber Doll, Rubber Ball, Rubber All\nAnd notwithstanding it's a dandy line of.`\nthe very best rubber toys, the prices\nE haven't been stretched. There's an Uui\nIJR elasticity of choice---not of cost\nDON'T LET THE HILDRENSEE THE il'\nUnless rubber is very good it quickly\nspoils and cracks in this climate.\nS These are made of the rubber that\nwon't. It's good rubber.\n0You can get it at Chapple 's\nEXhIBIT DRAWS\nTHE CROWDS\nDISPLAY OF PRODUCE MAKES HIT\nWITH VISITORS.\nBEGGED FOR SPECIMEN\nColorado 'Men Admit That. Yellow\nstone Valley Excels in Production of\nEverything-Ordinary Samples of\nWhat The Farmers Harvest.\n\"We have the show that is doing\nthe 'business when it comes to draw\ning the. crowd, said Secretary Decker\nof the Chamber of Commerce yester\nday in speaking of the 'produce exibit\nin the office of the organization. \"Ours\nseems to be a continous performance,\njudging from the people that are in\nand out througnout the daylight\nhours.\n\"Farmers and tourists from all parts\nof the east who stop over in this city\nen route to the coast or other points\nin the northwest, express great sur\nprise on viewing the array of produce\nwhich Mr. Gardiner has arranged, and\ntheir exclamations of wonderment are\nsome times amusing. A great many\ncome here predjudiced against Mon\ntana as an agricultural community,\nbut our exibit is enough to remove\nany doubts regarding the fertility of\nthe soil and the favorable climatic\nconditions for the production of all\nkinds of fruits, grains and vegetables.\nA party of Iowa men were in last\nweek and, although they said that the\nears of corn which we are exibiting\nare not as large as those raised back\nin the Hawk Eye state, they were\nforced to admit that we raised good\ncorn here.\nColoradoans See It.\n\"There were two gentlemen from\nColorado dropped in today and spent\na greater part of the forenoon view\ning the exibit. At first they were in\nclined to jest and draw unfavorable\ncomparisons between the produce of\nthe Yellowstone valley and the conai\ntions here and the produce and con\nditions in -their native state, but were\nfinally forced to admit that we have\nthem beaten when it come to agricul\ntural products and favorable condi\ntions for raising them. They stated\nthat in justice to this community they\nmust admit that we have them excelled\nwhen it comes to producing every\nthing including sugar beets of whlcn\nthey tell so much. Both of them ex\nto this section of Montana in the near\nfuture and ehgaging in farming.\n\"The questions asked by the visi\ntors show that the exibit makes\na hit with them and that they are\nnere for some other reason besides\nidle curiosity. Their inquiries are\nnot confined to farming conditions\nalone, a great many of them ask as to\noportunities for business locations\nin this city and as to available mar\nkets for live stock, and the cost of\nkeeping the same.\n\"One man from West Virginia hung\naround the ofice all one day last week\nand finally begged for a specimen\npotato and red onion to send Ito his\nbrother in the east. I gave it to him\nand he wrapped it up and expressel\nit at once.\nSunday' Visitors.\n\"Even Sunday, visitors viewed the\nexibit. A party of Iowa men who\nwere here and hearing of the display\nlooked up Mr. Gardiner and requested\nto be admitted to the building. 'Mr.\nGardiner showed them the exibit and\nI WANT TO BUY\nHAY GRAI\nW ,M ,CORSR\nlike all of the others .who had seen\nit they were very much surprteed.\nThe beauty of the whole thing is that\nwe can truthfully tell all of those wno\ncome to see us that the epecimens of\nproduce were not gathered especially\nfor the exibit, except that the riper\nspecimens which would not keep were.'\ndiscarded. Every bunch of grain, or.\nspecimen of fruit or'vegetable here, 1\nsimply a fair sample of the ordina r'\nproduce which the farmers harvested\nin the valley this fall.\"\nROGUES GALLERY\nBEING ALTERED\nREFURBISH -D AND GREATLY' IM\nPROVED.\nThat j1iotographis miseellaney\nknown as the \"rogues' gallery\" in the\npolice station, is undergoing repairs\nand rearrangement. For a long time\nthe circulars and warnings about\ncrooks, and many detached photo\ngraps, have been stuck anywise in a\npair ofold picture frames, but yester\nday Chief Talgo and Jailey Heagney\npurchased some slender gilt rods and\nnailed them to the wall of the Ealief's\noffice. Then the photographs were\ninstalled in regular order and'` se\nquence and Heagney and the chief\nstood off and exclaimed, \"Ain't that\nthe goods, though?\"\nA rogues' gallery is an essential\nequipment of every police office. In\nit are kept the protographs df men\nwho are \"wanted,\" of old crooks and\nbad \"yeggs,\" or escaped convicts and\ncirculars conveying information as to\nall the criminals in the country.\nIn the larger cities an accurate\nrecord of all these circulars and pro\ntograph is kept indexed, as well as\na record of all the deserters from the\narmy and navy of the country.\nThe change in the Billings' gallery\nis a move toward efficiency, though\nthere are many other ways in, which\nthe records of the Billings police sta\ntion could be improved.\nFORGED CHECKS\nIN WESTERN CITIES\nSYSTEMATICALL.Y PLIED GRAFT\nFOR ONE YEAR.\nLos Angeles, Oct. 28.-C. R. Howes,\nwho claims Portland, Ore., as. his\nhome, was arrested Saturday on a\ncharge of forgery and who is accused\nby the police of a systematic series\nof forgeries of checks aggregating a\nconsiderable sum in several western\ncities, was arraigned in Justice court\ntoday and his hearing on two charges'\nset for next Thursday. His bail was\nfixed .at $1500 in each case, which he\nwas unable to furnish.\nAccording to a confession which\nthe police claim to have secured from\nHowes, he has forged checks on'.an\nextensive scale in practically every\ncity of importance in the west, in\ncluding Salt Lake City, Denver, Ogden,\nButte, Kaheas City, Omaha, St. Louis\nand Portland. Howes claims his home\nis in Portland and that he operated\nfrom there. His first forgery, ,t is\nalleged, was committed a year, ago in\nSan Francisco. 'He was candy. maker\nby trade.\nhusband's financial enemies, and' now\nMr. Fish has triumphed over his pne\nmies. It is a happy time for the t 'i\nfamily, but iMr. Harriman will get','etn,\nyet if they don't watch out.-R ,ptib\nlican Picket.","height":"21288","width":"16008"}}
